     \"entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/app/bootstrap_page.cj::FoodikeBootstrap.buildHistoryRoute\"\n256:           ],\n257:           \"tests\": []\n258:         },\n259:         {\n260:           \"kind\": \"source-feature\",\n261:           \"featureId\": \"app-src-main-java-com-example-foodike-presentation-compo-047d189262-001-image-viewing-bitmap-exif-handling-zoom\",\n262:           \"featureName\": \"Image viewing, bitmap/exif handling, zoom, preview, or gallery display behavior.\",\n263:           \"sourcePath\": \"app/src/main/java/com/example/foodike/presentation/components/SearchBar.kt\",\n264:           \"importance\": \"critical\",\n265:           \"plannedPhase\": \"phase-04-home-history-discovery\",\n266:           \"status\": \"not-applicable\",\n267:           \"parityLevel\": \"not-applicable\",\n268:           \"verdict\": \"complete\",\n269:           \"reasons\": [\n270:             \"not-applicable has source/notes explanation\"\n271:           ],\n272:           \"targetEndpoints\": [],\n273:           \"tests\": []\n274:         },\n275:         {\n276:           \"kind\": \"source-feature\",\n277:           \"featureId\": \"app-src-main-java-com-example-foodike-presentation-compo-0411e44e98-004-observable-state-viewmodel-flow-livedata\",\n278:           \"featureName\": \"Observable state, ViewModel/Flow/LiveData/recomposition, or UI state propagation.\",\n279:           \"sourcePath\": \"app/src/main/java/com/example/foodike/presentation/components/SearchBar.kt\",\n280:           \"importance\": \"critical\",\n\n(Showing lines 1-280 of 1611. Use offset=281 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"schemaVersion\": 1,\n  \"generatedAt\": \"2026-06-25T16:18:44+00:00\",\n  \"phase\": \"phase-04-home-history-discovery\",\n  \"purpose\": \"Phase implementation-group verdicts generated after grouped implementation batches. Use this as a bounded group-repair queue before the normal phase coverage gate.\",\n  \"summary\": {\n    \"implementationGroups\": 5,\n    \"repairCandidates\": 2,\n    \"byVerdict\": {\n      \"complete\": 3,\n      \"incomplete\": 2\n    },\n    \"byPriority\": {\n      \"critical\": 5\n    }\n  },\n  \"repairPolicy\": {\n    \"repairableVerdicts\": [\n      \"incomplete\",\n      \"partial\"","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":"translation-inputs\\phase-group-verdicts.json","time":{"start":1782404337090,"end":1782404337098}},"id":"prt_eff93cd94001zKZJpt6N0Y65qt","sessionID":"ses_1006c5c95ffeP0kIq47sKblB1o","messageID":"msg_eff93bb75001kOe8auDjZNxqKD"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782404337421,"sessionID":"ses_1006c5c95ffeP0kIq47sKblB1o","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_c4M98vQyX0f1uDKuankhRPr8","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md","limit":260},"output":"<path>D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie Agent Protocol\n2: \n3: This protocol is the stable instruction source for `opencode-cj` sessions in the Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie workflow. Human operators and orchestration scripts may reference this file from generated prompts.\n4: \n5: ## 1. Role\n6: \n7: You are the translation agent for an Android Kotlin app to HarmonyOS Cangjie app migration.\n8: \n9: You perform the actual target-project source translation and target-project source fixes. You preserve the source app's user-visible behavior while adapting implementation, resources, data flow, state management, and build configuration to HarmonyOS Cangjie patterns.\n10: \n11: ## 2. Authority Boundaries\n12: \n13: - You may modify files under `<target-project>/`.\n14: - You may create or update `plan.md` and strict `plan.json` during planning.\n15: - Do not modify `<source-project>/`.\n16: - Do not modify `translation-inputs/` except when a prompt explicitly asks you to write a small deferred note there.\n17: - Do not modify `translation-records/`.\n18: - Do not modify workflow scripts, analyzer code, build-gate scripts, or this protocol unless the user explicitly asks for toolchain work.\n19: - Do not replace the orchestration flow with a separate translator, analyzer, or build system.\n20: - Do not assume app-specific names from previous migrations.\n21: \n22: ## 3. Required Inputs\n23: \n24: Read the relevant files before making decisions:\n25: \n26: - `task-planning.md`\n27: - `plan.md`\n28: - `plan.json`\n29: - `translation-inputs/preflight-report.md`\n30: - `translation-inputs/sdk-report.json`\n31: - `translation-inputs/skills-report.md`\n32: - `translation-inputs/plan-seed.md` and `translation-inputs/plan-seed.json` when present\n33: - `translation-inputs/source-feature-survey.md`\n34: - `translation-inputs/resource-coverage-report.md`\n35: - `translation-inputs/coverage-gap-report.md`\n36: - `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/gradle-model.json`\n37: - `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/analysis.json`\n38: - `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/locations.json`\n39: - `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/planning-note.md`\n40: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/manifest-summary.json`\n41: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/resource-map.json`\n42: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/screen-map.json`\n43: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/view-bindings.json`\n44: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/layout-tree.json`\n45: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/drawable-semantics.json`\n46: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/adapter-map.json`\n47: - `translation-inputs/android-analysis/behavior-spec.md`\n48: - `X2Cangjie/docs/harmonyos-cangjie-translation-checklist.md`\n49: - The current phase's `build-report.md`, if fixing a build blocker.\n50: - The current phase's `opencode-build-blocker-prompt.txt`, if fixing a build blocker.\n51: \n52: If an input is missing, continue only when the missing input is not essential for the requested step. Report the gap.\n53: \n54: `translation-inputs/kotlin-analysis/planning-note.md` may report multiple Kotlin or Java source roots. Treat that as the normal multi-module case and use the combined `analysis.json` plus source files as the structural reference for all modules.\n55: \n56: If multi-module analysis failed before translation planning because the analyzer protocol probe failed, do not work around it in the target project. Ask the operator to rebuild the analyzer instead of proceeding from partial static inputs.\n57: \n58: ## 3.1 Static Analysis Scope\n59: \n60: Treat `translation-inputs/` as structured planning evidence and indexes, not as a complete source of truth. Do not assume a source feature is absent only because it is missing from generated analysis.\n61: \n62: Use `source-feature-survey.md`, `resource-coverage-report.md`, and `coverage-gap-report.md` as a coverage baseline. Their purpose is to reduce functional gaps and unexplained code-scale gaps. Do not mechanically match source LoC; instead, map current-phase critical/high source files, resources, tests, and platform integrations to target implementation, supplemental tests, or explicit deferred items with source evidence and reason.\n63: \n64: For current-phase decisions:\n65: \n66: - Use structured inputs first to locate relevant source screens, composables, resources, data paths, settings/preferences, callbacks, navigation, persistence, Compose state, ViewModel/repository flow, and state-refresh behavior.\n67: - If behavior, resources, bindings, navigation, persistence, or state refresh semantics are unclear, inspect the minimal relevant source project files.\n68: - If source code contradicts or supplements generated analysis, follow the source code.\n69: - Report the analysis gap so later phases do not inherit a false assumption.\n70: \n71: ## 3.2 Kotlin-Specific Behavior Evidence\n72: \n73: When the source app uses Jetpack Compose, inspect composables, remembered state, state hoisting, callbacks, navigation routes, LazyColumn/LazyRow contents, dialogs, bottom bars, and event handlers before planning target files.\n74: \n75: When the source app uses XML/ViewBinding, inspect Activity/Fragment lifecycle flow, adapters, RecyclerView/ListView refresh behavior, click listeners, validation, and navigation before planning target files.\n76: \n77: When the source app uses ViewModel, StateFlow, LiveData, coroutine, repository, Room, Retrofit, Firebase, DataStore, or SharedPreferences, preserve the user-visible observable behavior even if the translated implementation uses local HarmonyOS-compatible abstractions.\n78: \n79: ## 4. Planning Session Requirements\n80: \n81: In a planning session, generate or update:\n82: \n83: - `plan.md`\n84: - `plan.json`\n85: \n86: `plan.md` must define the migration phases, phase goals, phase dependencies, build gates, review points, deferred items, and behavior risks.\n87: \n88: `plan.json` must be strict JSON and cover:\n89: \n90: - `files`: target files, source references, top-level definitions, and translation guidelines.\n91: - `assets`: strings, images, colors, layouts, styles, vectors, animations, menus, and resource adaptation rules.\n92: - `dependencies`: third-party dependencies and their HarmonyOS Cangjie replacement strategy.\n93: - `tests`: existing source tests to migrate, generated tests for uncovered core behavior, supplemental tests for shallow source coverage, and test commands or deferred validation.\n94: - `phases`: canonical phase identifiers, target scope, required inputs, expected files, implementation groups, and gate criteria.\n95: - `deferred`: known incomplete items, reason, owner phase, and validation needed.\n96: \n97: Planning must explicitly map:\n98: \n99: - `plan-seed` source units, callable function/composable/event-handler contracts, UI contracts, data contracts, resource contracts, platform capability contracts, structure risks, and analysis gaps to phases and implementation groups.\n100: - Kotlin classes, Android Activities, Fragments, ViewModels, repositories, Compose composables, XML/ViewBinding screens, adapters, listeners, callbacks, StateFlow/LiveData observers, and coroutine-driven side effects.\n101: - Android resources and layouts to HarmonyOS resources and ArkUI builders.\n102: - Persistence, backend SDKs, local storage, network APIs, and CRUD/data-flow behavior.\n103: - UI state, observable data, navigation, validation, error messages, and refresh semantics.\n104: - Source tests and project-specific verification assets to target tests or target-side validation cases.\n105: \n106: Each implementation group in `plan.json` should include stable `groupId`, `title`, `groupType`, `priority`, `sourcePaths`, source function/composable or callable contract references when available, `featureIds`, `resourceInputs`, `platformCapabilityIds`, UI/data contract references or hints, `expectedTargetDomains`, `requiredBehaviors`, `riskHints`, and `acceptanceEvidence`. Treat `plan-seed` as planning evidence, not a complete source of truth; inspect source files when behavior is unclear or when source code contradicts static analysis, and record `analysisGaps` or `sourceOverrides` instead of silently dropping behavior.\n107: \n108: Do not implement the migration during a planning-only session unless the human prompt explicitly authorizes it.\n109: \n110: ## 5. Build Phase Rules\n111: \n112: For every phase:\n113: \n114: - Re-read `task-planning.md`, `plan.md`, and `plan.json`.\n115: - Read the structured analysis inputs relevant to this phase.\n116: - Work only on the current phase's scope unless a small prerequisite fix is required.\n117: - Keep source-file structure understandable; do not collapse the app into one large file.\n118: - Prefer HarmonyOS Cangjie idioms and the checklist over Android or ArkTS assumptions.\n119: - Do not leave direct Android SDK, Firebase SDK, or unavailable third-party library references in target Cangjie code unless explicitly deferred with a replacement plan.\n120: - Migrate source tests relevant to the current phase. If source tests are absent or too shallow for current phase behavior, add focused target-side tests for translated business, data, state, validation, refresh, Compose state, ViewModel/repository flow, or persistence logic.\n121: - Prefer runnable target-project tests. If a behavior cannot be automated with the available template/SDK in this phase, keep the code testable and record the deferred validation path.\n122: - After edits, review the target project against `plan.md` and `plan.json`.\n123: - If `apply_patch` fails, read back affected files before retrying.\n124: - If a long session is interrupted, inspect the current filesystem state before continuing.\n125: \n126: ## 6. Build Blocker Fix Rules\n127: \n128: When fixing a build blocker:\n129: \n130: - Read `build-report.md`.\n131: - Read `opencode-build-blocker-prompt.txt`.\n132: - Fix the first visible blocker or the smallest coherent blocker class.\n133: - Do not perform unrelated redesigns.\n134: - Do not advance to a new phase.\n135: - Preserve phase intent and existing completed work.\n136: - Do not delete, disable, or weaken migrated/generated tests merely to make the build pass. Fix the implementation or record an explicit deferred test limitation when necessary.\n137: - After fixing, state which blocker was addressed and what still needs a build gate rerun.\n138: \n139: ## 7. Phase-End Checks\n140: \n141: At the end of a phase:\n142: \n143: - Check whether current target files contradict `plan.md` or `plan.json`.\n144: - Check whether the phase introduced files or code not needed by current or later phases.\n145: - Check whether UI state transitions and data refresh paths required by this phase are represented.\n146: - Check whether resources referenced by code exist in the target resource tree.\n147: - Check whether current-phase tests were migrated, generated, supplemented, run when possible, or explicitly deferred.\n148: - Check whether deferred state-machine, data-flow, backend, runtime, or resource gaps are recorded.\n149: \n150: ## 8. Prompt Templates\n151: \n152: ### Planning Session Template\n153: \n154: Use this shape when the orchestration script starts a planning session:\n155: \n156: ```text\n157: Read and follow the agent protocol: <agent-protocol>.\n158: Read and follow task-planning.md: <task-planning>.\n159: This is a planning session only.\n160: Generate or update <plan.md> and <plan.json>.\n161: Use translation-inputs as structured planning evidence.\n162: Do not modify source project files.\n163: Do not modify translation-records or workflow scripts.\n164: Report changed files, commands run, plan coverage, missing inputs, and deferred risks.\n165: ```\n166: \n167: ### Phase Session Template\n168: \n169: Use this shape when the orchestration script starts a phase session:\n170: \n171: ```text\n172: Read and follow the agent protocol: <agent-protocol>.\n173: Read task-planning.md, plan.md, and plan.json before editing.\n174: Start only phase <phase>.\n175: Use relevant translation-inputs and the HarmonyOS Cangjie checklist.\n176: Modify only the target project files needed for this phase.\n177: Do not skip phase-end checks.\n178: Report changed files, commands run, build status if known, plan changes, deferred issues, and next recommended action.\n179: ```\n180: \n181: ### Build Blocker Template\n182: \n183: Use this shape when the orchestration script starts a build-blocker fix session:\n184: \n185: ```text\n186: Read and follow the agent protocol: <agent-protocol>.\n187: Read the build blocker prompt: <opencode-build-blocker-prompt.txt>.\n188: Read the build report before editing.\n189: Fix only the current phase's build blocker or smallest coherent blocker class.\n190: Do not perform unrelated refactors.\n191: Report changed files, commands run, blocker addressed, remaining blockers, deferred issues, and next recommended action.\n192: ```\n193: \n194: ## 9. Required Final Response Format\n195: \n196: End every session with:\n197: \n198: ```text\n199: Changed files:\n200: - <path>: <what changed>\n201: \n202: Commands run:\n203: - <command or \"none\">\n204: \n205: Build result:\n206: - <PASS/FAIL/NOT RUN/UNKNOWN and report path if available>\n207: \n208: Plan changes:\n209: - <plan updates or \"none\">\n210: \n211: Deferred issues:\n212: - <issue, owner phase, validation needed, or \"none\">\n213: \n214: Next recommended action:\n215: - <one concrete next step>\n216: ```\n\n(End of file - total 216 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie Agent Protocol\n\nThis protocol is the stable instruction source for `opencode-cj` sessions in the Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie workflow. Human operators and orchestration scripts may reference this file from generated prompts.\n\n## 1. Role\n\nYou are the translation agent for an Android Kotlin app to HarmonyOS Cangjie app migration.\n\nYou perform the actual target-project source translation and target-project source fixes. You preserve the source app's user-visible behavior while adapting implementation, resources, data flow, state management, and build configuration to HarmonyOS Cangjie patterns.\n\n## 2. Authority Boundaries\n\n- You may modify files under `<target-project>/`.\n- You may create or update `plan.md` and strict `plan.json` during planning.\n- Do not modify `<source-project>/`.\n- Do not modify `translation-inputs/` except when a prompt explicitly asks you to write a small deferred note there.\n- Do not modify `translation-records/`.\n- Do not modify workflow scripts, analyzer code, build-gate scripts, or this protocol unless the user explicitly asks for toolchain work.\n- Do not replace the orchestration flow with a separate translator, analyzer, or build system.\n- Do not assume app-specific names from previous migrations.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"..\\..\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md","time":{"start":1782404337409,"end":1782404337419}},"id":"prt_eff93cdc3001HHKtTURCbkZxfv","sessionID":"ses_1006c5c95ffeP0kIq47sKblB1o","messageID":"msg_eff93bb75001kOe8auDjZNxqKD"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782404337587,"sessionID":"ses_1006c5c95ffeP0kIq47sKblB1o","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_9h6PnbIu6mqJByaVQODpSHfC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md","limit":260},"output":"<path>D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\plan.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Foodike HarmonyOS Cangjie Migration Plan\n2: \n3: ## Scope\n4: \n5: - Source project: `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`\n6: - Target project: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`\n7: - Session type: planning only\n8: - Source app shape: single-module Jetpack Compose app with splash-gated startup, Compose navigation, static fixture-backed content, and DataStore-backed login persistence.\n9: \n10: ## Confirmed Source Behavior\n11: \n12: - Startup uses `SplashViewModel` plus Android splash screen keep-on-screen behavior to resolve the first route before showing the app shell.\n13: - Initial route is `onboarding` when login state is false and `home` when login state is true.\n14: - Navigation shell owns the nav controller, a shared list scroll state, a floating cart button, and conditional bottom-bar visibility.\n15: - Onboarding is a three-page pager with next-step progression and final navigation to login.\n16: - Login stores only a boolean logged-in flag. Valid credentials are hard-coded to `abcxyz@gmail.com` and `abcdef`; invalid login emits a snackbar.\n17: - Home loads ads, recommended food cards, restaurant lists, and favourites from repositories. Selecting a restaurant stores the active restaurant in session state before navigating to detail.\n18: - History reads liked restaurants from the same session repository and also stores the selected restaurant before navigating to detail.\n19: - Restaurant detail reads the selected restaurant, derives recommended/non-veg/veg menu sections, toggles section expansion and local liked state, and shows the floating cart button only when the summed local item count is non-zero.\n20: - Cart currently reads repository cart snapshots but keeps bill totals, delivery restaurant, item-note editor, and quantity buttons mostly as local UI behavior with no persistent mutation wiring.\n21: - Profile shows static profile information and toggles the persisted login state on logout before clearing navigation history back to onboarding.\n22: - Real persistence is limited to login state. Restaurant selection, favourites, menu counts, liked state, and cart snapshots are in-memory session state only.\n23: \n24: ## Static Analysis Overrides\n25: \n26: - Generated platform-capability heuristics over-report media library, SAF/file access, runtime permissions, and notification/widget behavior. Source walkthrough evidence shows no actual media picker, external storage, SAF, dangerous permission request, service, receiver, widget, or notification flow in the app.\n27: - `Navigation.kt` contains a duplicated onboarding destination entry. Planning keeps the intended destination set but treats the duplicate as source cleanup noise, not a required user-visible behavior.\n28: - `SearchBar`, `ChipBar`, `MenuItemCard`, `ItemSection`, and some cart/detail interactions are currently local UI state only. They still matter for parity because the visible counters, filter chips, and note editors update immediately in-place.\n29: \n30: ## Target Architecture\n31: \n32: Plan the HarmonyOS Cangjie target around business domains instead of mirroring every Compose file one-for-one:\n33: \n34: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/app/` for app shell, startup, and route composition.\n35: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/domain/` for immutable models and route-safe view data.\n36: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/data/` for fixture loading, session repository logic, and preference-backed login state.\n37: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/features/onboarding|login|home|history|detail|cart|profile/` for feature stores and page composition.\n38: - `entry/src/main/cangjie/ohos_app_cangjie_entry/common/` for reusable widgets, formatting helpers, and resource adapters.\n39: - `entry/src/main/resources/base/` plus `AppScope/resources/` for strings, colors, images, app icon, startup visuals, and page profile wiring.\n40: \n41: Thin ability/page shell files may compose feature stores, but they should not absorb repository or preference logic.\n42: \n43: ## Phase Plan\n44: \n45: ### Phase 1: `phase-01-project-skeleton-resources`\n46: \n47: - Goal: bootstrap the HarmonyOS entry module, resource tree, startup wiring, and domain/data skeleton.\n48: - Key outputs:\n49:   - Target entry module from the mapcir skeleton.\n50:   - AppScope and entry metadata files.\n51:   - Core domain models.\n52:   - Resource catalog for strings, colors, and media copied/adapted from source drawables and mipmaps.\n53:   - Placeholder service boundaries for fixture content and persisted login state.\n54: - Gate:\n55:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-01-project-skeleton-resources`\n56: - Review focus:\n57:   - Entry package normalization to `ohos_app_cangjie_entry`.\n58:   - App icon, startup resources, and base strings exist.\n59:   - No broad shell file owns all business logic.\n60: \n61: ### Phase 2: `phase-02-startup-navigation-session`\n62: \n63: - Goal: implement startup route resolution, persisted login state, and the shared application shell.\n64: - Key outputs:\n65:   - Preference-backed login state service.\n66:   - Startup/session store that resolves first route before page composition.\n67:   - App navigation host with onboarding, login, home, history, cart, profile, and detail routes.\n68:   - Shared bottom-bar and floating cart-button shell behavior, including route and scroll gating.\n69: - Gate:\n70:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-02-startup-navigation-session`\n71: - Review focus:\n72:   - Startup does not flash the wrong initial page.\n73:   - Login/logout mutations immediately change visible navigation behavior.\n74:   - Route ownership remains separate from data services.\n75: \n76: ### Phase 3: `phase-03-onboarding-login-profile`\n77: \n78: - Goal: land the onboarding, login, and profile user flows with persisted session semantics.\n79: - Key outputs:\n80:   - Three-page onboarding sequence with progress indicators and next/final navigation behavior.\n81:   - Login form state, hard-coded credential validation, snackbar error path, and successful login transition to home.\n82:   - Profile page sections, static profile visuals, and logout mutation that clears the shell stack to onboarding.\n83: - Gate:\n84:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-03-onboarding-login-profile`\n85: - Review focus:\n86:   - Login failure messaging remains immediate and non-blocking.\n87:   - Persisted login state survives app restart semantics.\n88:   - Placeholder social/signup/profile edit actions are visibly retained as non-implemented affordances, not silently removed.\n89: \n90: ### Phase 4: `phase-04-home-history-discovery`\n91: \n92: - Goal: implement fixture-backed discovery screens and restaurant selection flow.\n93: - Key outputs:\n94:   - Fixture content repository and session repository.\n95:   - Home screen sections for top bar, greeting, search bar, ads, recommended cards, favourites, filters, and restaurant list.\n96:   - History page with tab state and favourite restaurant selection flow.\n97:   - Shared selection command that stores the current restaurant before detail navigation.\n98: - Gate:\n99:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-04-home-history-discovery`\n100: - Review focus:\n101:   - Favourite sections render only when non-empty.\n102:   - Filter chips and search bar preserve immediate local-state updates.\n103:   - Selection and navigation happen in the same order as the source: save restaurant first, then navigate.\n104: \n105: ### Phase 5: `phase-05-detail-cart-state-mutations`\n106: \n107: - Goal: implement restaurant detail, menu section expansion, local quantity controls, and cart rendering semantics.\n108: - Key outputs:\n109:   - Detail store fed by session-selected restaurant and repository snapshots.\n110:   - Recommended/non-veg/veg section grouping with expandable headers and icon rotation semantics.\n111:   - Local liked toggle state.\n112:   - Menu item quantity controls with immediate UI updates.\n113:   - Floating cart button visibility driven by non-zero summed item counts.\n114:   - Cart page sections for selected items, note editor, coupon input shell, delivery card, and bill section.\n115: - Gate:\n116:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-05-detail-cart-state-mutations`\n117: - Review focus:\n118:   - Immediate visible updates for expansion toggles, add/subtract controls, and note text.\n119:   - Detail-to-cart routing is preserved.\n120:   - Any simplification between local detail quantity state and repository cart state must be documented explicitly in coverage records if retained.\n121: \n122: ### Phase 6: `phase-06-polish-tests-verification`\n123: \n124: - Goal: close resource gaps, add focused tests, and verify high-risk behavior before row-level coverage backfill.\n125: - Key outputs:\n126:   - Target tests for session persistence, startup route resolution, login validation, route selection commands, and pure state reducers/helpers.\n127:   - Resource completeness check for missing strings and media references.\n128:   - Final build-gate evidence and any explicit deferred items recorded with risk.\n129: - Gate:\n130:   - `C:\\Users\\Sieger\\AppData\\Local\\Programs\\Python\\Python312\\python.exe D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\scripts\\shared\\reports\\build_hap_report.py --workspace-root D:\\workspace\\Foodike --target-project D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony --phase phase-06-polish-tests-verification`\n131: - Review focus:\n132:   - No unresolved string/media references.\n133:   - Target tests verify behavior that source tests did not cover.\n134:   - Coverage and capability backfill can proceed narrowly from the completed plan.\n135: \n136: ## Test Strategy\n137: \n138: - Source tests are only boilerplate examples and do not cover app behavior.\n139: - Add target-side tests for:\n140:   - login preference persistence and startup destination resolution\n141:   - login credential validation and snackbar error emission\n142:   - restaurant-selection command behavior\n143:   - detail section expansion and floating-cart visibility state\n144:   - filter helper mapping and any extracted formatting helpers\n145: - Prefer `cjpm test` where the target template supports it. If the HarmonyOS template blocks runnable tests, keep logic in small pure modules and record the exact harness limitation before relying on compile-only evidence.\n146: \n147: ## Resource Plan\n148: \n149: - Migrate all 52 source strings into HarmonyOS string resources before feature-complete review.\n150: - Copy and adapt all referenced bitmap/vector assets used by onboarding, login, cards, icons, splash, and app icon.\n151: - Convert Android theme values into HarmonyOS startup colors and page token resources.\n152: - Preserve content descriptions and user-facing labels where they are visible or accessibility-relevant.\n153: \n154: ## Platform Capability Decisions For Planning\n155: \n156: - Persisted preferences/login state: required and should map to a direct HarmonyOS preference/storage API.\n157: - Startup splash behavior: required, but exact API may be platform-replaced with HarmonyOS startup-page behavior if direct splash parity differs.\n158: - Localization resources: required and should map to HarmonyOS resource bundles.\n159: - Runtime permissions: currently not source-backed as a real user flow; keep as a reviewed capability row but do not plan first-phase implementation work for it.\n160: - Media library, SAF/file access, notifications/widgets: currently not source-backed; keep these out of active implementation scope unless later source inspection contradicts the walkthrough.\n161: \n162: ## Missing Inputs\n163: \n164: - `translation-inputs/plan-validation-report.md` and `.json` are missing.\n165: - `translation-inputs/phase-task-checklist.md` and `.json` are missing.\n166: - `translation-inputs/phase-capability-checklist.md` and `.json` are missing.\n167: - `translation-inputs/test-build-reports/` is missing.\n168: - Several Kotlin sidecar summaries listed in `task-planning.md` are missing, but the primary Kotlin analysis, locations, Android analysis, walkthrough, and source inspection were sufficient for planning.\n169: - `translation-inputs/mapcir/skeleton-hybrid/` is missing; the plain skeleton is present and sufficient for bootstrap planning.\n170: \n171: ## Deferred Risks\n172: \n173: - The source cart/detail mutation model is inconsistent: quantity changes are local to `MenuItemCard`, while cart data comes from a separate in-memory repository snapshot. Target implementation should preserve visible behavior first, but the final parity record may require an `implemented-simplified` note unless this mismatch is harmonized carefully.\n174: - Source search and chip filters currently keep local UI state without repository filtering logic. Removing them would be a regression, but over-implementing new filtering semantics would also diverge from source behavior.\n175: - Static analysis still tags many files with permissions/file/media concerns that are not source-backed. Coverage and platform records should be updated later with source-evidence notes to avoid false implementation pressure.\n176: - The target project is currently empty; phase 1 must establish a valid entry module before any row-level planned-phase backfill can safely validate target endpoints.\n\n(End of file - total 176 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Foodike HarmonyOS Cangjie Migration Plan\n\n## Scope\n\n- Source project: `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`\n- Target project: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`\n- Session type: planning only\n- Source app shape: single-module Jetpack Compose app with splash-gated startup, Compose navigation, static fixture-backed content, and DataStore-backed login persistence.\n\n## Confirmed Source Behavior\n\n- Startup uses `SplashViewModel` plus Android splash screen keep-on-screen behavior to resolve the first route before showing the app shell.\n- Initial route is `onboarding` when login state is false and `home` when login state is true.\n- Navigation shell owns the nav controller, a shared list scroll state, a floating cart button, and conditional bottom-bar visibility.\n- Onboarding is a three-page pager with next-step progression and final navigation to login.\n- Login stores only a boolean logged-in flag. Valid credentials are hard-coded to `abcxyz@gmail.com` and `abcdef`; invalid login emits a snackbar.\n- Home loads ads, recommended food cards, restaurant lists, and favourites from repositories. Selecting a restaurant stores the active restaurant in session state before navigating to detail.\n- History reads liked restaurants from the same session repository and also stores the selected restaurant before navigating to detail.\n- Restaurant detail reads the selected restaurant, derives recommended/non-veg/veg menu sections, toggles section expansion and local liked state, and shows the floating cart button only when the summed local item count is non-zero.\n- Cart currently reads repository cart snapshots but keeps bill totals, delivery restaurant, item-note editor, and quantity buttons mostly as local UI behavior with no persistent mutation wiring.","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"plan.md","time":{"start":1782404337572,"end":1782404337586}},"id":"prt_eff93cf9f001j7Uo7Un0Ni4MJA","sessionID":"ses_1006c5c95ffeP0kIq47sKblB1o","messageID":"msg_eff93bb75001kOe8auDjZNxqKD"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782404337589,"sessionID":"ses_1006c5c95ffeP0kIq47sKblB1o","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_1bYMMLrKq6A5EAUSYtGwWUQG","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\docs\\harmonyos-cangjie-translation-checklist.md","limit":260},"output":"<path>D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\docs\\harmonyos-cangjie-translation-checklist.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # HarmonyOS Cangjie Translation Checklist\n2: \n3: 面向 Android Java app 迁移到 HarmonyOS Cangjie 的阶段性检查表。它来自 Spendee 案例记录和后续构建修复经验，目标是在每个 `opencode-cj` phase 结束时先抓住高频编译/宏展开问题，再进入下一阶段。\n4: \n5: ## 使用时机\n6: \n7: 1. 每个翻译 phase 开始前，把本 phase 可能触及的条目加入 `opencode-cj` prompt。\n8: 2. 每个 phase 结束后，先运行完整构建门禁：\n9: \n10:    `<python>` 表示当前 Python 解释器：macOS/Linux 可用 `python3`，Windows 可用 `py -3` 或 `python`。\n11: \n12:    ```bash\n13:    <python> scripts/shared/reports/build_hap_report.py \\\n14:      --workspace-root <translation-workspace> \\\n15:      --target-project <target-project> \\\n16:      --phase <phase-name>\n17:    ```\n18: \n19: 3. 如果报告失败，把 `build-reports/<phase-name>/build-report.md` 和首个 blocker 交给 `opencode-cj` 修复当前 phase，不要先开启下一阶段。\n20: 4. 构建通过后，再进入运行时 smoke 或行为验证。\n21: \n22: ## 资源和字符串边界\n23: \n24: - 不要把 `@r(...)` / `AppResource` 直接当作普通 `String`。\n25: - UI prop 如果可能接收资源字符串，优先使用 `ResourceStr`，或在边界处做 SDK 支持的显式转换。\n26: - 不要对 `ResourceStr` 调用普通字符串方法，例如 `isEmpty()`；需要空态时使用独立 `Bool` 状态。\n27: - 迁移 Android `setText(...)` 时，确认 HarmonyOS 端有明确的状态赋值或可观察数据源驱动文本刷新。\n28: - 每次资源迁移后，检查 `string.json`、media 资源和实际 UI 引用，避免保留旧 placeholder key 或缺失 AppScope/entry 双层资源。\n29: \n30: ## Option 和控制流\n31: \n32: - 不要生成 Java/Kotlin 风格的 `Option.get()`。\n33: - 非 UI helper 中使用 `match`、显式 `case Some(...)` / `case None`，或当前 SDK 支持的安全访问 API。\n34: - UI 构建逻辑中避免直接让 `match` 分支裸露生成不兼容的 component 形态；需要时拆成命名 `@Builder`。\n35: - 启动/依赖注入状态建议拆成明确的 `Bool`、错误资源、服务 option 解包 helper，减少 `@Component` 宏失败面。\n36: \n37: ## 包结构和导入\n38: \n39: - 避免 root package 与 `pages` / `routing` 之间出现环形依赖。公共 route 类型优先放在 `routing` 或独立 models/helpers 包。\n40: - UI 文件中避免宽泛 `std.collection.*` 导入；它可能和 ArkUI 组件名冲突，例如 `Stack`。\n41: - 需要集合类型时优先显式导入或限定命名。\n42: - helper 类型如果会通过 public `@Component` 生成构造器暴露，确认类型本身也是必要的 public 可见性。\n43: - 不要把临时 template/cache 文件当成迁移输入；`.cache`、build output 和 diagnostic log 只作为诊断证据。\n44: \n45: ## ArkUI Component 和 Builder\n46: \n47: - `@BuilderParam` 优先传入命名 `@Builder` 方法，不要依赖未验证的 inline closure 或 trailing component block。\n48: - 自定义容器组件要按当前 SDK 支持的构造器/slot 形态实现，不能照搬 ArkTS 示例。\n49: - 校验 ArkUI named arguments 和 modifiers 来自当前 Cangjie HarmonyOS SDK 文档，而不是只参考 ArkTS。\n50: - 对 `@Component` macro 失败，先缩小到入口组件状态、构造器 public 类型、资源字符串类型和 `@Publish` 字段类型这四类高频根因。\n51: - 组件内部紧密相关的 owner state 文本可直接在 owning page builder 中渲染，避免子组件 prop 复用导致同会话文本不刷新。\n52: \n53: ## 状态和可观察集合\n54: \n55: - 路由和跨页面状态模型使用 SDK 支持的 `@Observed`、`@Publish` 和明确字段类型。\n56: - 需要列表变化驱动 UI 时，使用 `ObservedArrayList` 等 SDK 支持的数据源，并给 `ForEach` 提供稳定 key。\n57: - 不要假设 `ObservedArrayList` 是普通 iterator；辅助逻辑中用下标访问或 SDK 支持方法。\n58: - 跨组件变化的 prop 需要 `@Prop` / `@Link` / `@Watch` 等明确同步链路。\n59: - 对 primitive totals、余额、计数等关键展示值，保存/编辑/删除成功后优先执行明确赋值，避免只依赖持久化回读触发 UI。\n60: \n61: ## 测试迁移和验证\n62: \n63: - 源项目已有测试时，当前 phase 相关测试应迁移或改写为目标侧测试，验证翻译后的业务、数据、状态、资源或刷新行为。\n64: - 源项目没有测试时，应为核心可测试逻辑补充适量测试；源测试过少时，应优先补高风险行为测试。\n65: - 如果当前 SDK/模板不支持某类自动化测试，应保持代码可测试，并记录 deferred validation、替代验证方法和后续完成路径。\n66: - 不要为了通过构建直接删除、禁用或弱化已迁移/生成的测试；应修实现、修测试集成，或明确记录当前阶段测试限制。\n67: \n68: ## 构建配置和工具链\n69: \n70: - 完整 HAP 构建必须使用 DevEco Cangjie plugin 管理的 full SDK，例如 `~/.cangjie-sdk/<version>/cangjie`；standalone `~/.local/cangjie` 只能代表轻量 `cjc` / `cjpm` 可用。\n71: - 缺少 full SDK 时，应先安装/启用 DevEco Studio Cangjie plugin，再继续 full build gate。\n72: - 每阶段记录构建命令、失败阶段、首个 blocker 和已解决 blocker。\n73: - 常见阶段含义：\n74:   - `ohpm install`：依赖、registry、模板测试依赖或 oh-package 问题。\n75:   - `SyncCangjieResource`：资源生成、配置 schema、Cangjie build support 注入问题。\n76:   - `CompileCangjie`：Cangjie 语法、宏展开、包依赖、ArkUI API 问题。\n77:   - `PackageHap`：资源/loader/package 产物问题。\n78:   - `SignHap`：签名配置问题；未签名 debug HAP 通常可能只是 warning。\n79: - full build 通过前，不要把 standalone `cjpm check` 失败简单等同于 HAP 构建失败；两者依赖来源不同。\n80: \n81: ## opencode-cj 修复交接\n82: \n83: - `apply_patch` 失败后必须 read-back，因为失败可能部分落盘。\n84: - `L.map is not a function`、`apply_patch verification failed`、`Failed to read file to update` 要分开记录。\n85: - 长 phase 被打断或恢复时，先让 `opencode-cj` 检查文件系统当前状态，再继续，不要重复生成同名组件或服务。\n86: - 构建 blocker prompt 应包含：\n87:   - 当前 phase 名称。\n88:   - `build-report.md` 路径。\n89:   - 失败阶段。\n90:   - 首个 blocker message 和 location。\n91:   - 只修当前 phase blocker 的约束。\n92: \n93: ## Phase Gate 验收\n94: \n95: - `build_hap_report.py` 的 Markdown/JSON 报告存在。\n96: - 报告包含 command、result、failed stage、first blocker、warnings、HAP artifacts。\n97: - 如果失败，已有 `opencode-build-blocker-prompt.txt` 可直接交给 `opencode-cj`。\n98: - 如果成功，报告记录 full build gate 通过，且可把本 phase 的已知编译 blocker 标为 resolved。\n99: - 下一 phase 只能在构建通过，或用户明确批准带 blocker 继续时开始。\n100: \n101: ## Spendee 证据映射\n102: \n103: - `@r(...)` / `ResourceStr` 误用导致重复 generic inference 和 macro blocker。\n104: - `Option.get()` 在当前 SDK 下不可用，入口和服务解包需改为显式 `match`。\n105: - root/pages/routing 包循环会阻断 `CompileCangjie`。\n106: - UI 文件中的 `std.collection.*` 与 ArkUI `Stack` 名称冲突。\n107: - `@BuilderParam` 命名 builder 比 inline closure 更稳定。\n108: - `ObservedArrayList` 不能按普通 `for-in` 假设处理。\n109: - 同会话 finance totals 刷新最终需要 owner state、显式赋值和可观察列表配合，构建通过不能替代运行时刷新验证。\n110: - 如果 full SDK 在 Phase 1 就接入，许多 Cangjie/ArkUI 编译问题可以在引入当 phase 就暴露，而不是累积到最终构建。\n\n(End of file - total 110 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# HarmonyOS Cangjie Translation Checklist\n\n面向 Android Java app 迁移到 HarmonyOS Cangjie 的阶段性检查表。它来自 Spendee 案例记录和后续构建修复经验，目标是在每个 `opencode-cj` phase 结束时先抓住高频编译/宏展开问题，再进入下一阶段。\n\n## 使用时机\n\n1. 每个翻译 phase 开始前，把本 phase 可能触及的条目加入 `opencode-cj` prompt。\n2. 每个 phase 结束后，先运行完整构建门禁：\n\n   `<python>` 表示当前 Python 解释器：macOS/Linux 可用 `python3`，Windows 可用 `py -3` 或 `python`。\n\n   ```bash\n   <python> scripts/shared/reports/build_hap_report.py \\\n     --workspace-root <translation-workspace> \\\n     --target-project <target-project> \\\n     --phase <phase-name>\n   ```\n\n3. 如果报告失败，把 `build-reports/<phase-name>/build-report.md` 和首个 blocker 交给 `opencode-cj` 修复当前 phase，不要先开启下一阶段。\n4. 构建通过后，再进入运行时 smoke 或行为验证。","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"..\\..\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\docs\\harmonyos-cangjie-translation-checklist.md","time":{"start":1782404337579,"end":1782404337588}},"id":"prt_eff93cfa8001b1AaZbL3EYnYX4","sessionID":"ses_1006c5c95ffeP0kIq47sKblB1o","messageID":"msg_eff93bb75001kOe8auDjZNxqKD"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782404337591,"sessionID":"ses_1006c5c95ffeP0kIq47sKblB1o","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_dD1wV5zBjc3uvUnv4u34Lbs0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\task-planning.md","limit":240},"output":"<path>D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\task-planning.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Android Kotlin to HarmonyOS Cangjie Translation Plan\n2: \n3: ## Goal\n4: \n5: Translate the Android Kotlin project in `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike` into a HarmonyOS Cangjie project rooted at `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`, preserving main features, screen flow, resources, state changes, data behavior, tests, and user-visible side effects while adapting implementation to HarmonyOS Cangjie patterns.\n6: \n7: ## Paths\n8: \n9: - App name: `Foodike`\n10: - Source kind: `kotlin`\n11: - Translation workspace: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike`\n12: - Workspace standing instructions: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\AGENTS.md`\n13: - Source project: `D:\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\Foodike`\n14: - Target HarmonyOS Cangjie project: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\Foodike-Harmony`\n15: - Translation inputs: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs`\n16: - Translation records: `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-records`\n17: - Agent protocol: `D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\Kotlin2Cangjie\\docs\\android-kotlin-to-cangjie-agent-protocol.md`\n18: - HarmonyOS Cangjie checklist: `D:\\X2Cangjie\\X2Cangjie\\docs\\harmonyos-cangjie-translation-checklist.md`\n19: \n20: ## Role Split\n21: \n22: - The source project is read-only behavior evidence.\n23: - The target project is the only application source tree that `opencode-cj` may modify.\n24: - `translation-inputs/` may contain generated reports, static analysis from separate Kotlin/Android analysis tools and Gradle metadata export, mapcir reference artifacts, and the agent-maintained `source-coverage-matrix.json/md` and `platform-capability-check.json/md`. Treat generated reports as read-only planning evidence; update only the source coverage matrix and platform capability check when recording migration coverage status.\n25: - The mapcir output, when present, is a deterministic bootstrap/reference artifact. Use it for project structure, resources, dependencies, and initial skeleton only. Do not treat generated placeholders as final business logic.\n26: - The workflow scripts orchestrate preparation and validation only; `opencode-cj` performs semantic translation and build repair.\n27: \n28: ## Structured Inputs\n29: \n30: Always review these generated baseline inputs when present:\n31: \n32: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-discovery.md`\n33: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/plan-seed.md`\n34: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/plan-seed.json`\n35: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-feature-survey.md`\n36: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-file-inventory.md`\n37: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-coverage-matrix.md`\n38: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-coverage-matrix-report.md`\n39: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/verification-results.md`\n40: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs\\phase-task-checklist.md` when a phase session is running\n41: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/platform-capability-check.md`\n42: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/platform-capability-check-report.md`\n43: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/target-structure-report.md`\n44: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/resource-coverage-report.md`\n45: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/coverage-gap-report.md`\n46: \n47: Then inspect relevant files from the unified inventory:\n48: \n49: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-discovery.json`\n50: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/source-discovery.md`\n51: - `D:\\workspace\\Foodike\\translation-inputs/mapcir/*.mapci